1. Executive Summary & Objectives
TrashTalkSecurity is an application security (AppSec) learning platform focused on secure coding, static analysis (SAST), and vulnerability reasoning.
The platform provides hands-on labs where users analyze intentionally vulnerable code snippets and minimal web applications to identify, reason about, and remediate application-layer security flaws.
Unlike traditional DAST or exploitation-focused labs (e.g., browser‑driven payload exercises), TrashTalkSecurity emphasizes code review, data flow analysis, exploitability judgment, and correct remediation—reflecting how AppSec work is performed in real-world engineering environments.
Core Objectives

Train AppSec engineers to identify and reason about vulnerabilities at the source code level
Improve understanding of exploitability, impact, and secure remediation
Provide structured AppSec learning without red-team exploitation workflows
Demonstrate strong DevOps practices through the platform’s own infrastructure

Target Audience

Application Security Engineers
Software Engineers learning secure coding
Security-focused students and early-career professionals


2. User Personas & Stories
Persona: Application Security Engineer
Needs to assess code findings, reduce false positives, and guide development teams.
User Story

As an AppSec engineer, I want to review vulnerable code and determine whether it is exploitable, why it matters, and how it should be fixed.


Persona: Software Engineer
Wants to understand why their code is insecure and how to correct it properly.
User Story

As a developer, I want to learn what makes a code pattern vulnerable and how to remediate it correctly.


Persona: Student / Learner
Needs guided, structured exposure to application security concepts.
User Story

As a learner, I want interactive practice reviewing vulnerable code with clear explanations and feedback.


3. Functional Requirements
3.1 Authentication & Access

Username/password authentication
Role separation:

User – complete labs
Admin – manage labs/content


No external identity providers in v1


3.2 AppSec Labs
Labs are instructional, not adversarial.
Lab Types (v1 Scope)

SAST Code Review Labs

Small, focused code snippets
Multiple languages supported over time (e.g., Java, Python, JavaScript, Go)


Vulnerable Web/API Labs

Minimal applications designed for inspection and reasoning
Focus on logic flaws, validation issues, auth/authz weaknesses



Each lab includes:

Context and assumptions
Vulnerable code or application
Guided questions
Expected secure remediation


3.3 TrashTalk Engine (Critique & Guidance)
The TrashTalk engine provides:

Structured security critique of insecure code
Guided questions such as:

Is this vulnerable?
Under what conditions?
What is the impact?
How should it be fixed?


Concise, professional feedback with light humor

No exploit payloads are required to complete labs.

3.4 Grading & Validation

Rule-based validation of user responses
Static pattern checks and logic assertions
Pass/fail per question
Clear explanation of correct vs incorrect answers


3.5 Progress Tracking

Lab completion tracking
Per-lab pass/fail status
Optional scoring (non-competitive)


4. UI / UX Specifications
Design Principles

Code-first interface
Minimal, distraction-free layout
Clear separation between:

Code
Questions
Feedback/explanations



Key Views

Dashboard: available labs, completion status
Lab View: vulnerable code + context
Question View: guided prompts
Results View: reasoning and remediation explanation

Mobile support is not required.

5. Non-Functional Requirements
Security

No real-world targets
No exploit chains or automated attacks
Labs fully isolated and sandboxed
No persistent credentials in lab environments

Scalability

Stateless application services
Horizontal scaling for lab execution where applicable
Automatic teardown of temporary resources

Platform & Delivery

Web-based application
Kubernetes used for platform infrastructure
CI/CD used for build, test, and deployment
Infrastructure managed via Infrastructure-as-Code


6. Project Scope & Timeline
In Scope (v1)

AppSec-focused code labs
Vulnerable web/API labs
Automated evaluation and feedback
CI/CD and Kubernetes-based platform delivery

Out of Scope (v1)

Exploitation walkthroughs
Bug bounty workflows
Red-team tooling
Cloud misconfiguration training
Mobile applications

High-Level Milestones

Specification finalized and frozen
First “gold-standard” AppSec lab implemented
Lab evaluation engine completed
End-to-end deployment via CI/CD
Documentation and example labs published


7. Success Criteria
The project is successful if:

Users can correctly identify vulnerable code patterns
Users understand exploitability and impact without executing attacks
Users learn correct remediation strategies
New labs can be added without platform redesign
The platform remains aligned with AppSec, not exploitation, goals


8. Design Constraints & Non‑Goals (Hard Boundaries)
This project will not:

Teach attack payload construction
Require interacting with real production-like services
Simulate red-team engagements
Drift into cloud or infrastructure security labs

Any future enhancement must support application security learning.

9. Versioning & Change Control

This specification defines v1.0
Any scope change requires:

Explicit update to this document
Review against stated objectives and non-goals




